show_disparities_node.disparitiesPagetext: When population health or the quality of living environments varies by population characteristics such as income or race, there is disparity. One way to visualize disparity is to chart indicators of health or environment across levels of neighborhood poverty. We categorized neighborhoods as high, medium or low poverty. Then we took the median of the neighborhood-specific values in each category. The median is the middle of the sorted group of values.

info.info_how_calculated: Data collected at specific NYCCAS monitoring sites along with information about emissions sources were incorporated into a statistical model that predicted pollutant concentrations at all locations in NYC for the specified time period. The results were then smoothed using GIS, assigned to the appropriate NYC neighborhood, and averaged. The gaseous pollutants in NYC are measured in units of parts per billion.
info.info_source: New York City Community Air Survey

info.info_how_calculated: Neighborhoods are ranked according to the percent of people whose annual income falls below 100% of the federal poverty level. Rankings are then divided into 3 approximately equal groupings of low, medium and high poverty.
info.info_source: American Community Survey

link_data_node.linkDataPagetext: The "Link Data" function shows associations between environmental health data at the neighborhood level using <a href="http://a816-dohbesp.nyc.gov/IndicatorPublic/Glossary.aspx?#Scatterplot" target="_blank">scatterplots.</a> The points represent x and y values for each NYC neighborhood. The pairs of indicators available for scatterplots were chosen because previous research suggests that one may either directly or indirectly cause or contribute to the other. Because the data being charted are <a href="http://a816-dohbesp.nyc.gov/IndicatorPublic/Glossary.aspx?#Ecological_Study" target="_blank">ecological</a> and not individual level, and because many factors contribute to the health of a population or environment, the patterns seen in these charts do not necessarily represent the underlying causal relationship.

Compare.compare_type: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease  Hospitalization (Age-Adjusted Rate)
Compare.graph_title: Neighborhood Neighborhood Air Quality: Hospitalization by Sulfur Dioxide (SO2)
Compare.x_axis_title: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease  Hospitalization - Age-Adjusted Rate (per 10,000 residents) 2016

info.info_how_calculated:
Number of Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)-related hospitalizations among NYC residents aged 25 years and older, summed within 5-year age groups, and divided by the population in each age group using NYC DOHMH intercensal estimates; quotients are multiplied by the proportion of the 2000 US population in each age group. Age-adjusted rate is the sum of the weighted age-specific rates; expressed as cases per 10,000 residents.

 

Hospitalizations include ICD-9 principal diagnosis codes 490 (bronchitis, not specified as acute or chronic), 491 (chronic bronchitis), 492 (emphysema), 496 (chronic airway obstruction, not elsewhere classified), 493.2 (chronic obstructive asthma) or ICD-10 principal diagnosis codes J40 (bronchitis, not specified as acute or chronic), J41-J42 (chronic bronchitis), J43 (emphysema), or J44 (other COPD). Cases with 493.2 are excluded if none of the secondary diagnosis fields contain 490-492 or 496.

 

New York hospitals began using the ICD-10 system on October 1, 2015. Because the ICD systems differ in how they classify COPD, data are not comparable before and after 2015. Data from 2015 are not shown because they contain a combination of ICD-9 and ICD-10 principal diagnosis codes.
info.info_source: New York State Statewide Planning and Research Cooperative System (SPARCS) Deidentified Hospital Discharge Data

info.x_axis_title_reg: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease Emergency Department Visits
info.info_name: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease Emergency Department Visits
info.info_how_calculated:
Number of Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)-related emergency department (ED) visits among NYC residents aged 25 years and older, summed within 5-year age groups, and divided by the population in each age group using NYC DOHMH intercensal estimates; quotients are multiplied by the proportion of the 2000 US population in each age group. Age-adjusted rate is the sum of the weighted age-specific rates; expressed as cases per 10,000 residents.

 

ED visits include both patients who are treated and released in the ED (outpatients) and who are admitted as inpatients through the emergency department.

 

ED vists include ICD-9 principal diagnosis codes 490 (bronchitis, not specified as acute or chronic), 491 (chronic bronchitis), 492 (emphysema), 496 (chronic airway obstruction, not elsewhere classified), 493.2 (chronic obstructive asthma) or ICD-10 principal diagnosis codes J40 (bronchitis, not specified as acute or chronic), J41-J42 (chronic bronchitis), J43 (emphysema), or J44 (other COPD). Cases with 493.2 are excluded if none of the secondary diagnosis fields contain 490-492 or 496.

 

New York hospitals began using the ICD-10 system on October 1, 2015. Because the ICD systems differ in how they classify adult asthma, data are not comparable before and after 2015. Data from 2015 are not shown because they contain a combination of ICD-9 and ICD-10 principal diagnosis codes.
info.info_source: New York State Statewide Planning and Research Cooperative System (SPARCS) Deidentified Hospital Discharge Data

Number of asthma-related emergency department (ED) visits among NYC resident children up to 4 years old, divided by the population of children up to 4 years old, using NYC DOHMH intercensal estimates; expressed as cases per 10,000 residents.

 

ED visits include both patients who are treated and released in the ED (outpatients) and who are admitted as inpatients through the emergency department.

 

An ED visit is included if it has an ICD-9 principal diagnosis code of 493 or an ICD-10 principal diagnosis code of J45. New York hospitals began using the ICD-10 system on October 1, 2015. Because the ICD systems are similar in how they classify childhood asthma, data can be compared across years.

info.x_axis_title_reg: Public School Children (5-14 Yrs Old) with Persistent Asthma
info.info_name: Public School Children (5-14 Yrs Old) with Persistent Asthma
info.info_how_calculated: Number of public school children, aged 5-14 years, with a most recent asthma diagnosis reported to NYC DOHMH from the previous or current school year that describes symptoms occurring more than twice per week, divided by the 5-14 year old population, expressed per 1,000. Rates are calculated by residence of the child. Note: Use of a denominator consisting of all 5-14 year olds results in an underestimate of the true asthma prevalence, since the numerator represents only children enrolled in public schools that report to NYC DOHMH.
info.info_source: New York City Automated School Health Records

info.info_how_calculated: Data collected at specific NYCCAS monitoring sites along with information about emissions sources were incorporated into a statistical model that predicted pollutant concentrations at all locations in NYC for the specified time period. The results were then smoothed using GIS, assigned to the appropriate NYC neighborhood, and averaged. The gaseous pollutants in NYC are measured in units of parts per billion.
info_source: New York City Community Air Survey

info.info_how_calculated: Air samples collected at specific NYCCAS monitoring sites along with information about emissions sources were incorporated into a statistical model that predicted pollutant concentrations at all locations in NYC for the specific time period. The results were then assigned to the appropriate NYC neighborhood and the 10th percentile identified. The gaseous pollutants in NYC are measured in units of parts per billion.
info_source: New York City Community Air Survey

info.info_how_calculated: Air samples collected at specific NYCCAS monitoring sites along with information about emissions sources were incorporated into a statistical model that predicted pollutant concentrations at all locations in NYC for the specific time period. The results were then assigned to the appropriate NYC neighborhood and the 90th percentile identified. The gaseous pollutants in NYC are measured in units of parts per billion.
info_source: New York City Community Air Survey
